{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636271"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:25:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17577"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17577","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17577"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.17,0,0.35,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10267"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71366"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10267"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17577"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56841"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10070"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23988"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23999"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71366","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71366"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of chylomicrons?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transport dietary triglycerides from intestine to peripheral tissues","Transport triglycerides from liver to peripheral tissues","Transport phospholipids from liver to intestine","Transport cholesterol from intestine to liver","Transport cholesterol from peripheral tissues to liver"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of chylomicrons is to \u003Cstrong\u003Etransport dietary triglycerides from the intestine to peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E. After a meal containing fat, triglycerides are absorbed by intestinal epithelial cells, packaged into chylomicrons, and released into lymphatic vessels. They eventually enter the bloodstream via the thoracic duct, where they deliver their triglyceride content to peripheral tissues through the action of lipoprotein lipase.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport cholesterol from peripheral tissues to liver\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of high-density lipoproteins (HDL)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport triglycerides from liver to peripheral tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of very low-density lipoproteins (VLDL)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport phospholipids from liver to intestine\u003C/strong\u003E - This is not a major pathway of phospholipid transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransport cholesterol from intestine to liver\u003C/strong\u003E - While chylomicrons do carry some dietary cholesterol, their primary function is triglyceride transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EChylomicrons are unique among lipoproteins in that they contain apolipoprotein B-48 and are the only lipoprotein particles that enter circulation through the lymphatic system rather than being secreted directly into blood.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chylomicrons transport dietary triglycerides from the intestine to peripheral tissues via lymphatics and blood.","Chylomicrons are assembled in intestinal epithelial cells and contain apolipoprotein B-48.","Chylomicrons enter circulation through the thoracic duct, not the portal system."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56841"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17577"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56841"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-18T08:48:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-18T08:49:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10267"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71366"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-1